{"title_page": "Kali NetHunter", "text_new": "{{short description|Mobile penetration testing platform for Android devices powered by Kali Linux}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Kali NetHunter\n| logo = [[File:Kali_Linux_2.0_wordmark.svg]] <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = [[File:NetHunter-Homescreen.jpg|thumb|Kali NetHunter home screen]]\n| screenshot size = 300px\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = \n| developer = [[Offensive Security]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2014|09|24}} <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 2020.1\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|01|28|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = 2020.2-pre3\n| latest preview date = {{Start date and age|2020|04|01|df=yes/no}}\n| repo = {{URL|https://gitlab.com/kalilinux/nethunter/}}\n| programming language = C, Java, Kotlin, Python, Bash\n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Android (operating system)|Kali Linux]]\n| platform = [[ARM architecture|armhf, aarch64]]\n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = Various\n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.kali.org/kali-linux-nethunter/}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n'''Kali NetHunter''' is a mobile penetration testing platform for Android devices, based on [[Kali Linux]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/kali-nethunter/wiki|title=offensive-security/kali-nethunter|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> Official images are published by Offensive Security for the most popular of the supported devices, such as Nexus 5/5X/6P, OnePlus 1/2/7 (T/Pro), Xiaomi Mi 9T, Samsung Galaxy Tab S4, etc. Many more models are supported and images not published by Offensive Security can be generated using the NetHunter build scripts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.androidauthority.com/how-to-install-kali-nethunter-android-896887/|title=Here's how to install Kali NetHunter on any Android device|date=2018-08-13|website=Android Authority|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> It is maintained by a large community and funded by [[Offensive Security]].\n\n== Background and history ==\nStarted in 2014, the Kali Linux NetHunter project is the first [[Open-source license|Open Source]] Android penetration testing platform for [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices, created as a joint effort between the Kali community member \u201cBinkyBear\u201d and [[Offensive Security]], the company behind the [[Kali Linux]] desktop distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kali.org/kali-linux-nethunter/|title=Kali Linux NetHunter|date=2014-08-29|website=www.kali.org|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 2019, the list of supported Android devices has grown to over 50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/security/meldung/Werkzeug-fuer-Sicherheitsforscher-Das-neue-Kali-Linux-ist-da-4430136.html|title=Werkzeug f\u00fcr Sicherheitsforscher: Das neue Kali Linux ist da|last=Schirrmacher|first=Dennis|date=May 23, 2019|website=heise online|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nKali NetHunter is an Android ecosystem, the core of which is a ROM overlay that consists of the following core components:\n\n* a custom [[Kernel (operating system)|kernel]] with various enhancements to allow for wifi injection, HID attacks, etc.\n* a Kali Linux [[chroot]] container\n* a NetHunter Android application, which allows for easier interaction with various security tools and attacks\n* a client to access the NetHunter App Store offering dozens of purpose build cyber security apps\n* a custom built boot animation\n* background services and system tools that provides a framework for various penetration testing tools\n* Kali dEsktop eXperience (KEX) that allows to run a full Kali Linux Desktop environment on Android devices with tools to output the desktop via HDMI or wirelesly\n\n<br />\n[[File:NetHunter KEX.jpg|none|thumb|403x403px|Kali NetHunter Desktop Experience (KEX)]]\nIn addition to the [http://tools.kali.org/ penetration testing tools] featured on desktop Kali Linux, NetHunter also enables Wireless 802.11 [[frame injection]], one-click MANA [[Evil twin (wireless networks)|Evil Access Points]], HID keyboard functionality (for [https://www.pjrc.com/teensy/ Teensy]-like attacks), as well as BadUSB [[Man-in-the-middle attack|man-in-the-middle]]  (MitM) attacks. \n\n<br />\n\n== NetHunter App Store ==\nKali Nethunter has an applications store based on a fork of [[F-Droid]] with telemetry completely removed. The store has about 30 applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-linux.de/news/1/27259/app-store-f%C3%BCr-kali-nethunter.html|title=App-Store f\u00fcr Kali NetHunter|website=Pro-Linux|language=de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Attacks and tools ==\n\n=== NetHunter BadUSB Attack ===\nEnabling this USB mode will turn a device with a [[USB On-The-Go]] cable into a network interface when plugged into a target computer. Connecting the USB cable to a PC will force all traffic from that PC (Windows or Linux) through the NetHunter device, which allows the device's user to perform a [[Man-in-the-middle attack|man-in-the-middle]] (MitM) attack<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/kali-nethunter/wiki/NetHunter-BadUSB|title=offensive-security/kali-nethunter|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>.\n\n=== MANA Evil Access Point ===\nMANA is an \"evil access-point\" implementation by SensePost that performs rogue [[Wireless access point|WAP]] and [[Man-in-the-middle attack|MitM]] attacks. The MitM logs get written to <code>/var/lib/mana-toolkit/</code> in the Kali chroot. Users can change the access point's configuration to match their target environment, such as the [[SSID]], channel number, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/nethunter-app/wiki/MANAEvilAccessPoint|title=offensive-security/nethunter-app|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== NetHunter HID Keyboard Attacks ===\nThe NetHunter HID Attacks turn any device and its OTG USB cable into a pre-programmed keyboard, able to type any given commands. It is functionally similar to \u201cTeensy\u201d type devices.\n\n== Reception ==\nJohn Callaham of Android Authority wrote an unofficial guide for installing Kali NetHunter on most Android devices.<ref name=\":0\" /> The installation processes and operations have been described in detail in ''Hands-On Penetration Testing with Kali NetHunter: Spy on and protect vulnerable ecosystems using the power of Kali Linux for pentesting on the go'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Glen D.|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=6guLDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=kali+%22nethunter%22+android&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMorKfxpnoAhVD_aQKHRqgDlMQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=kali%20%22nethunter%22%20android&f=false|title=Hands-On Penetration Testing with Kali NetHunter: Spy on and protect vulnerable ecosystems using the power of Kali Linux for pentesting on the go|last2=Oriyano|first2=Sean-Philip|date=2019-02-28|publisher=Packt Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78899-668-6|language=en}}</ref> and ''Kali Linux - An Ethical Hacker's Cookbook: Practical recipes that combine strategies, attacks, and tools for advanced penetration testing''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sharma|first=Himanshu|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=j8-PDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA391&dq=kali+%22nethunter%22+android&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMorKfxpnoAhVD_aQKHRqgDlMQ6AEIPDAC#v=onepage&q=kali%20%22nethunter%22%20android&f=false|title=Kali Linux - An Ethical Hacker's Cookbook: Practical recipes that combine strategies, attacks, and tools for advanced penetration testing, 2nd Edition|date=2019-03-29|publisher=Packt Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78995-370-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software|Computer programming}}\n* [[Kali Linux]]\n*[[Offensive Security]]\n*[[Offensive Security Certified Professional]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.kali.org/docs/nethunter/ Kali Nethunter Documentation]\n\n{{Android}}\n{{GNU/Linux distributions}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:ARM operating systems]]\n[[Category:Custom Android firmware]]\n[[Category:Debian-based distributions]]\n[[Category:Digital forensics software]]\n[[Category:Free security software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mobile penetration testing platform for Android devices powered by Kali Linux}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Kali NetHunter\n| logo = [[File:Kali_Linux_2.0_wordmark.svg]] <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = [[File:NetHunter-Homescreen.jpg|thumb|Kali NetHunter home screen]]\n| screenshot size = 300px\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = \n| developer = [[Offensive Security]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2014|09|24}} <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 2020.1\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|01|28|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = 2020.2-pre3\n| latest preview date = {{Start date and age|2020|04|01|df=yes/no}}\n| repo = {{URL|https://gitlab.com/kalilinux/nethunter/}}\n| programming language = C, Java, Kotlin, Python, Bash\n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Android (operating system)|Kali Linux]]\n| platform = [[ARM architecture|armhf, aarch64]]\n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = Various\n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.kali.org/kali-linux-nethunter/}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n'''Kali NetHunter''' is a mobile penetration testing platform for Android devices, based on [[Kali Linux]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/kali-nethunter/wiki|title=offensive-security/kali-nethunter|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> Official images are published by Offensice Security for the most popular of the supported devices, such as Nexus 5/5X/6P, OnePlus 1/2/7 (T/Pro), Xiaomi Mi 9T, Samsung Galaxy Tab S4, etc. Many more models are supported and images not published by Offensive security can be generated using the NetHunter build scripts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.androidauthority.com/how-to-install-kali-nethunter-android-896887/|title=Here's how to install Kali NetHunter on any Android device|date=2018-08-13|website=Android Authority|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> It is maintained by a large community and funded by [[Offensive Security]].\n\n== Background and history ==\nStarted in 2014, the Kali Linux NetHunter project is the first [[Open-source license|Open Source]] Android penetration testing platform for [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices, created as a joint effort between the Kali community member \u201cBinkyBear\u201d and [[Offensive Security]], the company behind the [[Kali Linux]] desktop distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kali.org/kali-linux-nethunter/|title=Kali Linux NetHunter|date=2014-08-29|website=www.kali.org|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 2019, the list of supported Android devices has grown to over 50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/security/meldung/Werkzeug-fuer-Sicherheitsforscher-Das-neue-Kali-Linux-ist-da-4430136.html|title=Werkzeug f\u00fcr Sicherheitsforscher: Das neue Kali Linux ist da|last=Schirrmacher|first=Dennis|date=May 23, 2019|website=heise online|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nKali NetHunter is an Android ecosystem, the core of which is a ROM overlay that consists of the following core components:\n\n* a custom [[Kernel (operating system)|kernel]] with various enhancements to allow for wifi injection, HID attacks, etc.\n* a Kali Linux [[chroot]] container\n* a NetHunter Android application, which allows for easier interaction with various security tools and attacks\n* a client to access the NetHunter App Store offering dozens of purpose build cyber security apps\n* a custom built boot animation\n* background services and system tools that provides a framework for various penetration testing tools\n* Kali dEsktop eXperience (KEX) that allows to run a full Kali Linux Desktop environment on Android devices with tools to output the desktop via HDMI or wirelesly\n\n<br />\n[[File:NetHunter KEX.jpg|none|thumb|403x403px|Kali NetHunter Desktop Experience (KEX)]]\nIn addition to the [http://tools.kali.org/ penetration testing tools] featured on desktop Kali Linux, NetHunter also enables Wireless 802.11 [[frame injection]], one-click MANA [[Evil twin (wireless networks)|Evil Access Points]], HID keyboard functionality (for [https://www.pjrc.com/teensy/ Teensy]-like attacks), as well as BadUSB [[Man-in-the-middle attack|man-in-the-middle]]  (MitM) attacks. \n\n<br />\n\n== NetHunter App Store ==\nKali Nethunter has an applications store based on a fork of [[F-Droid]] with telemetry completely removed. The store has about 30 applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-linux.de/news/1/27259/app-store-f%C3%BCr-kali-nethunter.html|title=App-Store f\u00fcr Kali NetHunter|website=Pro-Linux|language=de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Attacks and tools ==\n\n=== NetHunter BadUSB Attack ===\nEnabling this USB mode will turn a device with a [[USB On-The-Go]] cable into a network interface when plugged into a target computer. Connecting the USB cable to a PC will force all traffic from that PC (Windows or Linux) through the NetHunter device, which allows the device's user to perform a [[Man-in-the-middle attack|man-in-the-middle]] (MitM) attack<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/kali-nethunter/wiki/NetHunter-BadUSB|title=offensive-security/kali-nethunter|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>.\n\n=== MANA Evil Access Point ===\nMANA is an \"evil access-point\" implementation by SensePost that performs rogue [[Wireless access point|WAP]] and [[Man-in-the-middle attack|MitM]] attacks. The MitM logs get written to <code>/var/lib/mana-toolkit/</code> in the Kali chroot. Users can change the access point's configuration to match their target environment, such as the [[SSID]], channel number, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/offensive-security/nethunter-app/wiki/MANAEvilAccessPoint|title=offensive-security/nethunter-app|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== NetHunter HID Keyboard Attacks ===\nThe NetHunter HID Attacks turn any device and its OTG USB cable into a pre-programmed keyboard, able to type any given commands. It is functionally similar to \u201cTeensy\u201d type devices.\n\n== Reception ==\nJohn Callaham of Android Authority wrote an unofficial guide for installing Kali NetHunter on most Android devices.<ref name=\":0\" /> The installation processes and operations have been described in detail in ''Hands-On Penetration Testing with Kali NetHunter: Spy on and protect vulnerable ecosystems using the power of Kali Linux for pentesting on the go'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Glen D.|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=6guLDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=kali+%22nethunter%22+android&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMorKfxpnoAhVD_aQKHRqgDlMQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=kali%20%22nethunter%22%20android&f=false|title=Hands-On Penetration Testing with Kali NetHunter: Spy on and protect vulnerable ecosystems using the power of Kali Linux for pentesting on the go|last2=Oriyano|first2=Sean-Philip|date=2019-02-28|publisher=Packt Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78899-668-6|language=en}}</ref> and ''Kali Linux - An Ethical Hacker's Cookbook: Practical recipes that combine strategies, attacks, and tools for advanced penetration testing''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sharma|first=Himanshu|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=j8-PDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA391&dq=kali+%22nethunter%22+android&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMorKfxpnoAhVD_aQKHRqgDlMQ6AEIPDAC#v=onepage&q=kali%20%22nethunter%22%20android&f=false|title=Kali Linux - An Ethical Hacker's Cookbook: Practical recipes that combine strategies, attacks, and tools for advanced penetration testing, 2nd Edition|date=2019-03-29|publisher=Packt Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78995-370-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software|Computer programming}}\n* [[Kali Linux]]\n*[[Offensive Security]]\n*[[Offensive Security Certified Professional]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.kali.org/docs/nethunter/ Kali Nethunter Documentation]\n\n{{Android}}\n{{GNU/Linux distributions}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:ARM operating systems]]\n[[Category:Custom Android firmware]]\n[[Category:Debian-based distributions]]\n[[Category:Digital forensics software]]\n[[Category:Free security software]]\n", "name_user": "Re4sonkernel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kali_NetHunter"}
{"title_page": "Benton End", "text_new": "[[File:Benton End House.JPG|thumb|The house viewed from the road]]\n'''Benton End''' is a Grade II* [[listed building|listed]]  sixteenth-century house located on the outskirts of the market town of [[Hadleigh, Suffolk|Hadleigh]] in [[Suffolk]], England. From 1939 to 1982 it was home to the artist [[Cedric Morris]], who ran the [[East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing]] in the house, and in the garden grew a significant botanical collection.\n==The Building==\nBenton End is thought to have been built in the 1520s. The first documented inhabitant is Robert Rolfe, a cloth merchant and \"chief inhabitant\" of Hadleigh<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sydenham |first1=Henry Augustus Hervey |title=Suffolk in 1524: Being the Return for a Subsidy Granted in 1523 |date=1910 |publisher=G. Booth |location=Michigan State University}}</ref>. Although later alterations have seen the house partly plastered and bay windows added, the original late-medieval timber stucture with brick [[nogging]] remains intact and visible in parts of the house, including the current main entrance <ref>{{cite web |title=Benton End House |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1194592 |website=Historic England |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==List of Notable Owners and Residents==\n*Parliamentarian [[John Bourchier (regicide)|John Bourchier]] inherited Benton End  in 1627 after marrying into the Rolfe family.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Andrews |first1=Sue |title=The story of Benton End in Hadleigh, Suffolk |journal=The Hadleigh Historian |date=2017 |issue=5}}</ref> \n*Botanist [[Adam Buddle]] may have grown up in the house, as his father inherited the house from his uncle the owner in 1686<ref>{{cite web |title=Will of Adam Buddle |url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D756968 |website=Gentleman of Hadleigh, Suffolk |publisher=The National Archives, Kew |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Buddle was known as an expert in [[bryophytes]], and the genus [[Buddleja]] was named in his honour.\n*Artist and horticulturalist [[Cedric Morris]] lived at Benton End from 1939 to his death in 1982.\n\n==East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing==\n{{Main|East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing}}\nCedric Morris and his partner [[Arthur Lett-Haines]] acquired Benton End in 1939 after fire destroyed the previous site of their art school in [[Dedham, Essex]]<ref>[https://www.questia.com/magazine/1P3-251576871/creative-outsiders Andrew Lambirth ''Creative outsiders'' The Spectator, ,  Nov 9, 2002]</ref>. Benton End afforded space for Morris, Lett-Haines and many of their students to live as well as work at the School. This contributed to the communal atmosphere, and encouraged its laissez-faire but inspiring approach to learning. Jon Lys Turner's biography of illustrator [[Richard Chopping]] and his partner Denis Wirth-Miller, both alumni of the East Anglian School, characterises it as \n{{Quote|text=a place for the free exchange of artistic ideas and techniques. The school was anti-hierarchical as well as anti-patriarchal, with little in the way of structure or rules, and provided a setting for sexual as well as artistic liberation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>}} While Morris focused on the students' work, Lett-Haines was in charge of the school's administration as well as cooking two meals a day. Thanks to Morris' work in the vegetable garden and Lett-Haines' enthusiasm for cooking, the community at Benton End did not experience hardships on the scale of wartime London - indeed, according to Lys Turner, the war years were \"markedly hedonistic\".\n\nThrough the 40s and 50s Benton End became the centre of a diverse community of twentieth-century artists, writers and horticulturalists<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3724/is_/ai_n9158512 Andrew Lambirth ''Creative outsiders'' The Spectator, ,  Nov 9, 2002]</ref>. Among the students was [[Lucian Freud]], who was a favourite of Morris and Lett-Haines despite his waywardness<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Freud called Morris' portraits \"revealing in a way that is almost improper\", leading commentators to view Morris as a significant influence on Freud's style<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bird |first1=Michael |title=Cedric Morris, the artist who taught Lucian Freud to paint |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/cedric-morris-artist-taught-lucian-freud-paint/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=2 August 2019}}</ref>. Friends and visitors included the painters [[John Nash]] and [[Francis Bacon]], and writers [[Ronald Blythe]] and [[Stephen Spender]]. Blythe described the atmosphere of Benton End as \"robust and coarse, and exquisite and tentative all at once. Rough and ready and fine mannered. Also faintly dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gayford |first1=Martin |title=A whiff of wine and garlic |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/a-whiff-of-wine-and-garlic |website=The Spectator |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Illustrator [[Kathleen Hale]], who wrote the [[Orlando (fictional cat)|Orlando the Marmalade Cat]] series, was also a frequent visitor to Benton End, as Lett-Haines' lover and as a friend and informal pupil of Morris<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Cedric Morris\u2019 Garden==\nMorris grew rare and exotic plants at Benton End, which he collected on expeditions to the Mediterranean and North Africa and in many cases introduced to cultivation in Britain for the first time<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Matthew |title=The botanic guardians saving unfashionable plants from extinction |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a483ee18-6721-11e7-9a66-93fb352ba1fe |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Financial Times |date=21 July 2017}}</ref>. He planted them in an idiosyncratic style which admirers have viewed as an extension of his work as a painter: Beth Chatto described the garden as a \"bewildering, mind-stretching, eye-widening canvas of colour, textures and shapes\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chatto |first1=Beth |title=A sage in Suffolk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2001/sep/15/weekend7.weekend10 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>. He was most prolific as a cultivator of irises: he grew around 1,000 varieties, and bred up to 90 cultivars of his own<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Neve |first1=Christopher |title=A Painter and his Garden: Cedric Morris at Benton End |journal=Country Life |date=17 May 1979}}</ref><ref name=\"McWaters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html|title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return|last=McWaters|first=Paula|date=18 April 2015|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>. His rose, Rosa 'Sir Cedric Morris' and poppy <i>Papaver orientale</i> 'Cedric Morris' are both widely commercially available.\n\nThe garden Morris created, and the plants he grew, influenced many important figures in British horticulture. [[Constance Spry]] displayed rhubarb from his garden in her London shop<ref>{{cite news |last1=Woodward |first1=Christopher |title=Artist plantsman Cedric Morris and his 'paradise of pollen and paint\u2019 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/gardening-events/artist-plantsman-cedric-morris-paradise-pollen-paint/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=7 April 2018}}</ref>, and [[Vita Sackville-West]], a frequent visitor to Benton End, grew his irises at [[Sissinghurst]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWaters |first1=Paula |title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2015}}</ref>. Most significantly, Morris became a mentor to [[Beth Chatto]], who said that a large proportion of the plants in her [[Beth Chatto Gardens|gardens]] came from Benton End<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chatto |first1=Beth |title=A sage in Suffolk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2001/sep/15/weekend7.weekend10 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>. \n\nSarah Cook, former head gardener at Sissinghurst who grew up in Hadleigh, is leading a project to track down, preserve and record all Cedric Morris' surviving introductions. Many of these were distributed to other horticulturalists after Morris' death by Jenny Robinson, whom Morris appointed as his horticultural executor. In 2015 Sarah Cook showed 25 Cedric Morris irises at the Chelsea Flower Show<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWaters |first1=Paula |title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2015}}</ref>.\n\n==Present Day==\nThe house has been acquired by the Pinchbeck Charitable Trust, which hopes to restore Morris' garden and establish the house as an education centre in art and horticulture, as well as a memorial to Morris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arkell |first1=Roland |title=Modern British Art: Rediscovered Cedric Morris painting to be sold to benefit Benton End |url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/print-edition/2019/september/2410/feature/modern-british-art-return-to-the-end/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Antiques Trade Gazette |publisher=Metropress Ltd |date=23 Sep 2019}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Hadleigh, Suffolk]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Benton End House.JPG|thumb|The house viewed from the road]]\n'''Benton End''' is a Grade II* [[listed building|listed]]  sixteenth-century house located on the outskirts of the market town of [[Hadleigh]] in [[Suffolk]]. From 1939 to 1982 it was home to the artist [[Cedric Morris]], who ran the [[East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing]] in the house, and in the garden grew a significant botanical collection.\n==The Building==\nBenton End is thought to have been built in the 1520s. The first documented inhabitant is Robert Rolfe, a cloth merchant and \"chief inhabitant\" of Hadleigh<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sydenham |first1=Henry Augustus Hervey |title=Suffolk in 1524: Being the Return for a Subsidy Granted in 1523 |date=1910 |publisher=G. Booth |location=Michigan State University}}</ref>. Although later alterations have seen the house partly plastered and bay windows added, the original late-medieval timber stucture with brick [[nogging]] remains intact and visible in parts of the house, including the current main entrance <ref>{{cite web |title=Benton End House |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1194592 |website=Historic England |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==List of Notable Owners and Residents==\n*Parliamentarian [[John Bourchier (regicide)|John Bourchier]] inherited Benton End  in 1627 after marrying into the Rolfe family.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Andrews |first1=Sue |title=The story of Benton End in Hadleigh, Suffolk |journal=The Hadleigh Historian |date=2017 |issue=5}}</ref> \n*Botanist [[Adam Buddle]] may have grown up in the house, as his father inherited the house from his uncle the owner in 1686<ref>{{cite web |title=Will of Adam Buddle |url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D756968 |website=Gentleman of Hadleigh, Suffolk |publisher=The National Archives, Kew |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Buddle was known as an expert in [[bryophytes]], and the genus [[Buddleja]] was named in his honour.\n*Artist and horticulturalist [[Cedric Morris]] lived at Benton End from 1939 to his death in 1982.\n\n==East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing==\n{{Main|East Anglian School of Painting and Drawing}}\nCedric Morris and his partner [[Arthur Lett-Haines]] acquired Benton End in 1939 after fire destroyed the previous site of their art school in [[Dedham, Essex]]<ref>[https://www.questia.com/magazine/1P3-251576871/creative-outsiders Andrew Lambirth ''Creative outsiders'' The Spectator, ,  Nov 9, 2002]</ref>. Benton End afforded space for Morris, Lett-Haines and many of their students to live as well as work at the School. This contributed to the communal atmosphere, and encouraged its laissez-faire but inspiring approach to learning. Jon Lys Turner's biography of illustrator [[Richard Chopping]] and his partner Denis Wirth-Miller, both alumni of the East Anglian School, characterises it as \n{{Quote|text=a place for the free exchange of artistic ideas and techniques. The school was anti-hierarchical as well as anti-patriarchal, with little in the way of structure or rules, and provided a setting for sexual as well as artistic liberation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>}} While Morris focused on the students' work, Lett-Haines was in charge of the school's administration as well as cooking two meals a day. Thanks to Morris' work in the vegetable garden and Lett-Haines' enthusiasm for cooking, the community at Benton End did not experience hardships on the scale of wartime London - indeed, according to Lys Turner, the war years were \"markedly hedonistic\".\n\nThrough the 40s and 50s Benton End became the centre of a diverse community of twentieth-century artists, writers and horticulturalists<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3724/is_/ai_n9158512 Andrew Lambirth ''Creative outsiders'' The Spectator, ,  Nov 9, 2002]</ref>. Among the students was [[Lucian Freud]], who was a favourite of Morris and Lett-Haines despite his waywardness<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Freud called Morris' portraits \"revealing in a way that is almost improper\", leading commentators to view Morris as a significant influence on Freud's style<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bird |first1=Michael |title=Cedric Morris, the artist who taught Lucian Freud to paint |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/cedric-morris-artist-taught-lucian-freud-paint/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=2 August 2019}}</ref>. Friends and visitors included the painters [[John Nash]] and [[Francis Bacon]], and writers [[Ronald Blythe]] and [[Stephen Spender]]. Blythe described the atmosphere of Benton End as \"robust and coarse, and exquisite and tentative all at once. Rough and ready and fine mannered. Also faintly dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gayford |first1=Martin |title=A whiff of wine and garlic |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/a-whiff-of-wine-and-garlic |website=The Spectator |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Illustrator [[Kathleen Hale]], who wrote the [[Orlando (fictional cat)|Orlando the Marmalade Cat]] series, was also a frequent visitor to Benton End, as Lett-Haines' lover and as a friend and informal pupil of Morris<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lys Turner |first1=Jon |title=The Visitors' Book: In Francis Bacon's Shadow: The Lives of Richard Chopping and Denis Wirth-Miller |date=2016 |publisher=Constable |location=Great Britain |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i12sCwAAQBAJ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Cedric Morris\u2019 Garden==\nMorris grew rare and exotic plants at Benton End, which he collected on expeditions to the Mediterranean and North Africa and in many cases introduced to cultivation in Britain for the first time<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Matthew |title=The botanic guardians saving unfashionable plants from extinction |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a483ee18-6721-11e7-9a66-93fb352ba1fe |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Financial Times |date=21 July 2017}}</ref>. He planted them in an idiosyncratic style which admirers have viewed as an extension of his work as a painter: Beth Chatto described the garden as a \"bewildering, mind-stretching, eye-widening canvas of colour, textures and shapes\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chatto |first1=Beth |title=A sage in Suffolk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2001/sep/15/weekend7.weekend10 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>. He was most prolific as a cultivator of irises: he grew around 1,000 varieties, and bred up to 90 cultivars of his own<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Neve |first1=Christopher |title=A Painter and his Garden: Cedric Morris at Benton End |journal=Country Life |date=17 May 1979}}</ref><ref name=\"McWaters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html|title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return|last=McWaters|first=Paula|date=18 April 2015|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>. His rose, Rosa 'Sir Cedric Morris' and poppy <i>Papaver orientale</i> 'Cedric Morris' are both widely commercially available.\n\nThe garden Morris created, and the plants he grew, influenced many important figures in British horticulture. [[Constance Spry]] displayed rhubarb from his garden in her London shop<ref>{{cite news |last1=Woodward |first1=Christopher |title=Artist plantsman Cedric Morris and his 'paradise of pollen and paint\u2019 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/gardening-events/artist-plantsman-cedric-morris-paradise-pollen-paint/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=7 April 2018}}</ref>, and [[Vita Sackville-West]], a frequent visitor to Benton End, grew his irises at [[Sissinghurst]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWaters |first1=Paula |title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2015}}</ref>. Most significantly, Morris became a mentor to [[Beth Chatto]], who said that a large proportion of the plants in her [[Beth Chatto Gardens|gardens]] came from Benton End<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chatto |first1=Beth |title=A sage in Suffolk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2001/sep/15/weekend7.weekend10 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>. \n\nSarah Cook, former head gardener at Sissinghurst who grew up in Hadleigh, is leading a project to track down, preserve and record all Cedric Morris' surviving introductions. Many of these were distributed to other horticulturalists after Morris' death by Jenny Robinson, whom Morris appointed as his horticultural executor. In 2015 Sarah Cook showed 25 Cedric Morris irises at the Chelsea Flower Show<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWaters |first1=Paula |title=Chelsea 2015: Cedric Morris irises return |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/chelseaflowershow/11545006/Chelsea-2015-Cedric-Morris-irises-return.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2015}}</ref>.\n\n==Present Day==\nThe house has been acquired by the Pinchbeck Charitable Trust, which hopes to restore Morris' garden and establish the house as an education centre in art and horticulture, as well as a memorial to Morris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arkell |first1=Roland |title=Modern British Art: Rediscovered Cedric Morris painting to be sold to benefit Benton End |url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/print-edition/2019/september/2410/feature/modern-british-art-return-to-the-end/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Antiques Trade Gazette |publisher=Metropress Ltd |date=23 Sep 2019}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benton_End"}
{"title_page": "1992 Brit Awards", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = 12th Brit Awards\n| image = \n| date = 12 February 1992\n| venue = [[Hammersmith Apollo]]\n| host = [[Simon Bates]]\n| previous = [[1991 Brit Awards|1991]]\n| main = [[Brit Awards]]\n| next = [[1993 Brit Awards|1993]]\n| most_awards = [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] (3)\n| most_nominations = [[The KLF]] and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] (4)\n| network = [[BBC]]\n}}\nThe '''1992 [[Brit Awards]]''' were the 12th edition of the biggest annual [[pop music]] awards in the [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1992|title=History|website=BRIT Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>. They are run by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and took place on 12 February 1992 at [[Hammersmith Apollo]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brits.co.uk/about-us/bpi|title=BPI|website=BRIT Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\n* [[Beverley Craven]] \u2013 \"[[Promise Me (song)|Promise Me]]\"\n* [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] \u2013 \"[[More Than Words]]\"\n* [[The KLF]] vs [[Extreme Noise Terror]] \u2013 \"[[3 a.m. Eternal]]\"\n* [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[All Woman]]\"\n* [[P.M. Dawn]] \u2013 \"[[Set Adrift on Memory Bliss]]\"\n* [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 \"[[Crazy (Seal song)|Crazy]]\"\n* [[Simply Red]] \u2013 \"[[Stars (Simply Red song)|Stars]]\"\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#bebebe\"\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Producer of the Year|British Producer of the Year]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 ''[[Seal (1991 album)|Seal]]'''''\n** [[Beverley Craven]] \u2013 ''[[Beverley Craven (album)|Beverley Craven]]''\n** [[The KLF]] \u2013 ''[[The White Room (KLF album)|The White Room]]''\n** [[Massive Attack]] \u2013 ''[[Blue Lines]]''\n** [[Simply Red]] \u2013 ''[[Stars (Simply Red album)|Stars]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Trevor Horn]]'''\n** [[David A. Stewart]]\n** [[Johnny Marr]]\n** [[Mark Knopfler]]\n** [[Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n** [[Youth (musician)|Youth]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Single of the Year|British Single of the Year]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Video of the Year|British Video of the Year]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Queen (band)|Queen]] \u2013 \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"'''\n** [[Gareth Hale]] and [[Norman Pace]] \u2013 \"The Stonk\"\n** [[Iron Maiden]] \u2013 \"[[Bring Your Daughter... to the Slaughter]]\"\n** [[Jason Donovan]] \u2013 \"[[Any Dream Will Do (song)|Any Dream Will Do]]\"\n** [[The KLF]] \u2013 \"[[3 a.m. Eternal]]\"\n** [[Vic Reeves]] and [[The Wonder Stuff]] \u2013 \"[[Dizzy (Tommy Roe song)|Dizzy]]\"\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 \"[[Killer (Adamski song)|Killer]]\"'''\n** [[Airhead (band)|Airhead]] \u2013 \"Funny How\"\n** [[Billy Bragg]] \u2013 \"[[Sexuality (Billy Bragg song)|Sexuality]]\"\n** [[Erasure]] \u2013 \"[[Love to Hate You]]\"\n** [[The KLF]] \u2013 \"[[Last Train to Trancentral]]\"\n** [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[Change (Lisa Stansfield song)|Change]]\"\n** [[Midge Ure]] \u2013 \"Cold, Cold Heart\"\n** [[Shakespears Sister]] \u2013 \"[[Goodbye Cruel World (Shakespears Sister song)|Goodbye Cruel World]]\"\n** [[Simply Red]] \u2013 \"[[Stars (Simply Red song)|Stars]]\"\n** [[The Wonder Stuff]] \u2013 \"The Size of a Cow\"\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Male Solo Artist|British Male Solo Artist]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Female Solo Artist|British Female Solo Artist]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Seal (musician)|Seal]]'''\n** [[Elton John]]\n** [[George Michael]]\n** [[Kenny Thomas (singer)|Kenny Thomas]]\n** [[Phil Collins]]\n** [[Van Morrison]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Lisa Stansfield]]'''\n** [[Annie Lennox]]\n** [[Beverley Craven]]\n** [[Cathy Dennis]]\n** [[Zo\u00eb (British singer)|Zo\u00eb]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Group|British Group]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[The KLF]] and [[Simply Red]]'''\n** [[Dire Straits]]\n** [[James (band)|James]]\n** [[Pet Shop Boys]]\n** [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Beverley Craven]]'''\n** [[Cathy Dennis]]\n** [[EMF (band)|EMF]]\n** [[Kenny Thomas (singer)|Kenny Thomas]]\n** [[Seal (musician)|Seal]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | Outstanding Contribution to Music\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for International Solo Artist|International Solo Artist]] \n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Freddie Mercury]]'''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Prince (musician)|Prince]]'''\n** [[Bryan Adams]]\n** [[Enya]]\n** [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n** [[Michael Bolton]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for International Group|International Group]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for International Breakthrough Act|International Breakthrough Act]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[R.E.M.]]'''\n** [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]]\n** [[Guns N' Roses]]\n** [[INXS]]\n** [[U2]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[P.M. Dawn]]'''\n** [[Chris Isaak]]\n** [[Color Me Badd]]\n** [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]]\n** [[Harry Connick Jr.]]\n** [[Jellyfish (band)|Jellyfish]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for Classical Recording|Classical Recording]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for Soundtrack/Cast Recording|Soundtrack/Cast Recording]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Georg Solti]]'''\n** [[Osmo V\u00e4nsk\u00e4]]\n** [[Jane Glover]]\n** [[John Eliot Gardiner]]\n** [[Leonard Bernstein]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''''[[The Commitments (film)|The Commitments]]'''''\n** ''[[The Doors (film)|The Doors]]''\n** ''[[Five Guys Named Moe]]''\n** ''[[Inspector Morse (TV series)|Inspector Morse]]''\n** ''[[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves]]''\n|}\n\n==Multiple nominations and awards==\nThe following artists received multiple awards and/or nominations.\n[[File:Seal 2012.jpg|right|200px|upright|thumb|alt=|Three-time winner [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] as most nominations and awards]]\n{{col-float}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Artists that received multiple nominations\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:55px;\" |Nominations\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Artist\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|4\n|[[The KLF]]\n|-\n|[[Seal (musician)|Seal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|3\n|[[Beverley Craven]]\n|-\n|[[Simply Red]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|2\n|[[Cathy Dennis]]\n|-\n|[[Extreme (band)|Extreme]]\n|-\n|[[Kenny Thomas (singer)|Kenny Thomas]]\n|-\n|[[Lisa Stansfield]]\n|-\n|[[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n|-\n|[[The Wonder Stuff]]\n|}\n{{col-float-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Artists that received multiple awards\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:55px;\" |Awards\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Artist\n|-\n|3\n|[[Seal (musician)|Seal]]\n|}\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1992 1992 Brit Awards at Brits.co.uk]\n\n{{Brit Awards}}\n\n[[Category:Brit Awards]]\n[[Category:1992 music awards|BRIT Awards]]\n[[Category:1992 in the United Kingdom|BRIT Awards]]\n[[Category:1992 in British music]]\n[[Category:1992 awards in the United Kingdom|Brit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = 12th Brit Awards\n| image = \n| date = 12 February 1992\n| venue = [[Hammersmith Apollo]]\n| host = [[Simon Bates]]\n| previous = [[1991 Brit Awards|1991]]\n| main = [[Brit Awards]]\n| next = [[1993 Brit Awards|1993]]\n| most_awards = [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] (3)\n| most_nominations = [[The KLF]] and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] (4)\n| network = [[BBC]]\n}}\nThe '''1992 [[Brit Awards]]''' were the 12th edition of the biggest annual [[pop music]] awards in the [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1992|title=History|website=BRIT Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>. They are run by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and took place on 12 February 1992 at [[Hammersmith Apollo]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brits.co.uk/about-us/bpi|title=BPI|website=BRIT Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\n* [[Beverley Craven]] \u2013 \"[[Promise Me (song)|Promise Me]]\"\n* [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] \u2013 \"[[More Than Words]]\"\n* [[The KLF]] vs [[Extreme Noise Terror]] \u2013 \"[[3 a.m. Eternal]]\"\n* [[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[All Woman]]\"\n* [[P.M. Dawn]] \u2013 \"[[Set Adrift on Memory Bliss]]\"\n* [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 \"[[Crazy (Seal song)|Crazy]]\"\n* [[Simply Red]] \u2013 \"[[Stars (Simply Red song)|Stars]]\"\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#bebebe\"\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Producer of the Year|British Producer of the Year]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Seal (musician)|Seal]] \u2013 ''[[Seal (1991 album)|Seal]]'''''\n** [[Beverley Craven]] \u2013 ''[[Beverley Craven (album)|Beverley Craven]]''\n** [[The KLF]] \u2013 ''[[The White Room (KLF album)|The White Room]]''\n** [[Massive Attack]] \u2013 ''[[Blue Lines]]''\n** [[Simply Red]] \u2013 ''[[Stars (Simply Red album)|Stars]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Trevor Horn]]'''\n** [[David A. Stewart]]\n** [[Johnny Marr]]\n** [[Mark Knopfler]]\n** [[Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n** [[Youth (musician)|Youth]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Single of the Year|British Single of the Year]]\n! width=\"50%\" | [[Brit Award for British Video of the Year|British Video of the Year]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''[[Queen (band)|Queen]] \u2013 \"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\"'''\n** [[Gareth 